<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>    The beauty of EverQuest, aside from its subscription model, is that players effectively pay to entertain each other. Sony just provides the playground: more than 1,000 computers in San Diego that have kept the game running since 1999. EverQuest also relies on 47 staffers to continually add items and quests to the game; another 128 &quot;game masters&quot; function as customer service reps and patrol the world answering questions. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Certainly, EverQuest's revenues are chicken feed to Sony. One hit movie from its Columbia Pictures unit can make two or three times what EverQuest brings in. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>    the game continues to add 12,000 players a month. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  I believe this</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
For the most part, at this stage of the &quot;game&quot;, we (as players) don't leave.  Of course some do permanently, but I think many continue the subscription or give it to someone who continues the subscription.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    They are profitable with the level of service they are providing.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I found this interesting:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>    The result is a game so addictive that the typical player spends 20 hours a week on EverQuest. That's about 8.6 million man-hours a month devoted to the game. (It took 7 million man-hours spread over 14 months to build the Empire State Building.) One-third of players 18 and older spend more time in the game world than they do at their paying jobs<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Great Article, thanks.<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/ulhyra.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lhyra</A> at: 8/13/02 2:31:59 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/ulhyra.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lhyra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cons Dubious </span><br>  Posts: 108<br> <font color=#333333>(8/13/02 2:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=71.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: So why don't those bastiches at Verant treat us better??</span><hr size=1> I didn't know Sony owned all of Verant, and this statement felt disjointed from the story..but<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A year after the breakup, Sony bought the rest of Verant for $32 million. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So...really....there is no more Verant.  It is all Sony using the Verant name. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/ucorwildelyonhart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Corwil Delyonhart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Scowls at you rdy to attack!</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#333333>(8/13/02 3:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=71.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: So why don't they treat us better???</span><hr size=1> Exactly - it's very rare that you deal with someone online who is getting paid money from verant to provide service to it's customers. <br>
<br>
Most of them are players who work 15-20 hours a month(last I read). In return for this they get their fee waved (10bucks or so depending on how you pay) and free expansions (40 bucks bonus a year). <br>
<br>
So that is considerably less than one dollar an hour. Which is what four or so dollars less than minimum wage in the US these days ? <br>
<br>
And yes I understand that legally they are considered &quot;volunteers&quot; and the things I am listing are &quot;perks&quot; of volunteering. <br>
<br>
However I like to understand the exact commitment to a company of someone that I am dealing with them. It makes it much easier to understand what to expect. No way to say this without sounding negative but bluntly when talking to a guide I am polite but really don't expect anything at all. They are being compensated far less than a fast food worker for their time. <br>
<br>
This isn't to say I am knocking all guides either, guides can be as great as someone working in a soup kitchen - really care and doing the best that they can. Or it can be a teenager paying for his EQ fix, or someone worse. <br>
<br>
In any case it's not really what most companies would consider service. And I can't really connect it to a traditional volunteer who generally works for a non profit organization helping out what they feel is a worthy cause for their time. There isn't any indication that I can see of a reasonable likelyhood of their heart being in their job, like there is with say a Red Cross Volunteer or some such. <br>
<br>
Now expand that out a bit, if your front line support(guides) isn't likely to resolve any significant amount of problems beyond the easily fixed, what is that going to do to your second line of support the paid support people( GMs) ? <br>
<br>
Simple answer - Stress and overwork. <br>
<br>
That's the in game support system that Verant has in place from my consumer point of view. A team of volunteers who are players as guides, and a relative handful of other support who are GM's and the phone support people etc. <br>
<br>
I am polite to all of them because yelling at a support rep helps nothing really, and it is a person on the other end. But if you have a basic understanding of the system you have it's pretty obvious not to expect a whole heck of a lot.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/usinghawkstormbringer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Singhawk Stormbringer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cons Threateningly </span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#333333>(8/14/02 4:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=71.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Adding to that</span><hr size=1> Remember, your expansion purchase and monthly fees go toward servers, internet connection, paying the devs, GMs, techs, etc.  So, by rights, when you can't get in for a day or whatever or can't do anything for a day... break it down as to how much you'd get back in a refund if they were an option.<br>
<br>
$13/month - 30 days - under 2 cents per hour and under 50 cents a day... if you work minimum wage for 1 hour per day, you've made that and then some <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So when Guide A tells you he can't do anything... more than likely... either VI said &quot;Nope, can't do it&quot; or they just don't have the power to do it.  It's not their fault... as I like to say (having been in a similar situation myself)... don't shoot the messenger. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/ukharnebloodyhand.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kharne Bloodyhand</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cons Amiable </span><br>  Posts: 350<br> <font color=#333333>(8/14/02 6:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=71.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.creativegraphixs.com/grfxfrlts/img1.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Adding to that</span><hr size=1> This wasn't aimed at the in game support.  This was aimed at the big assed managers who couldn't tell a MMORPG from a FPS, and could give a rats ass about us as customers... <p>Kharne Bloodyhand <BR>
